Because $\triangle ABD$ in the picture is an equilateral triangle, so let $\triangle ABD$'s height, $h,$ satisfy $3\times\cfrac{h}{2} = 1$, so $h=\cfrac{2}{\sqrt{3}}$. Then the height of $\triangle PEC$ also must be $\cfrac{2}{\sqrt{3}}$. On the other hand, let $F$ be a point located at $\cfrac{2}{\sqrt{3}}$ away from $E$ towards $C$. Since the height of $\triangle PEC$ is exactly the same as that of $\triangle PEF$, so $FP$ is perpendicular to $EC$. Therefore, the foot $F$ of the altitude of $\triangle PEC$ must lie on $EC$. Since
\begin{align}
\overline{EF} &= \cfrac{2}{\sqrt{3}}-\cfrac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\times\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} = \cfrac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\times(1-\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}),\tag{1}\\
\overline{EC} &= \sqrt{3},\tag{2}
\end{align}
\begin{align}
\cfrac{\overline{EF}}{\overline{EC}} &= \cfrac{\cfrac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\times(1-\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2})}{\sqrt{3}} = \cfrac{2(1-\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2})}{3},\tag{3}
\end{align}
so $EC$ must divide $FP$ into two parts so that the larger part is $\cfrac{2(1-\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2})}{3}$ times $EC,$ and therefore, the smaller part is $\cfrac{\cfrac{1}{3}+\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{6}}{1+\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{3}}\times EC,$ which is also the distance from $F$ to $C$. But $F$ lies within $\triangle \triangle PEC,$ the altitude from $P$ to $EC$ must also hit the triangle, therefore the distance from $F$ to $C$ in the picture must be the distance from $P$ to $EC$ in the picture. And because
\begin{align}
\overline{PA} &= \cfrac{3}{\sqrt{3}}=1,\\
\overline{AC} &= \sqrt{3},
\end{align}
\begin{align}
\cfrac{\overline{PA}}{\overline{AC}} &= \cfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}} = \cfrac{1}{1+\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{3}},\tag{4}
\end{align}
then the solution is $=1+\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{3}$. But the solution is also
\begin{align}
&\Big(\cfrac{2}{3}+\cfrac{2}{3}\cfrac{1-\sqrt{2}}{2}\Big)\times(1+\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{3})\\
=&\cfrac{2}{3}[1+\cfrac{1-\sqrt{2}}{3}]\times(1+\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{3}) = \Big(1+\cfrac{\sqrt{2}}{3}\Big)^2 =\Big(\cfrac{3+\sqrt{2}}{3}\Big)^2, 
\end{align}
