response:
Let  $r_1$  and  $n$  be the lower base radius and the number of all the terms in the prism, respectively. The lateral surface area i.e.  $A$  is expressed by the sum of the areas of all the lateral faces of the prism, or\begin{align*}
A &= 4 \times r_1 \times h_1 + 4 \times r_1 \times h_2 + \cdots + 4 \times r_1 \times h_{n - 1}
\ &= 4 \times r_1 \times (h_1 + h_2 + \cdots + h_{n - 1})\end{align*> Our goal is to find the values of  $h_1 + h_2 + \cdots + h_{n - 1}$ . Applying the Pythagorean theorem to the side view diagram, we obtain\begin{align*}
(h_1)^2 + (2 r_1)^2 &= (2 r_2)^2 \\
h_1 &= 2 r_1 \times \sqrt{3}
\end{align*}Similarly,\begin{align*}
h_2 &= 2 r_2 \times \sqrt{3} \\
&= 2 \times 2 r_1 \times \sqrt{3} \times \sqrt{3} \\
&= (2 r_1)^2 \times \sqrt{3}
\end{align*}Continuing with this process, we find that\begin{align*}
h_3 &= ((2 r_1)^2)^2 \times \sqrt{3} \\
h_4 &= ((2 r_1)^2)^3 \times \sqrt{3} \\
&\vdots \\
h_{n - 1} &= ((2 r_1)^2)^{n / 2 - 2} \times \sqrt{3}
\end{align*}Thus,\begin{align*}
h_1 + h_2 + \cdots + h_{n - 1} &= (2 r_1 \times \sqrt{3}) \times \left(1 + (2 r_1)^2 + ((2 r_1)^2)^2 + \cdots + ((2 r_1)^2)^{n / 2 - 2} \right) \\
&= (2 r_1 \times \sqrt{3}) \times \left(1 + 12 + 12^2 + \cdots + 12^{n / 2 - 2} \right)
\end{align*}The series in the parentheses is the partial sum of a geometric series whose first term is 1 and the common ratio is 12, leading to\begin{align*}
h_1 + h_2 + \cdots + h_{n - 1} &= (2 r_1 \times \sqrt{3}) \times \left(\frac{12^{n / 2 - 1} - 1}{11} \right) \\
A &= 4 \times r_1 \times (h_1 + h_2 + \cdots + h_{n - 1}) \\
&= \frac{8 \times r_1^2 \times \sqrt{3}}{11} \times \left(12^{n / 2 - 1} - 1\right) \\
&= \boxed{\frac{428 \sqrt{3}}{11}}
\end{align*}> Answer: $\text{(D)} \frac{428\sqrt{3}}{11}$

